page.title: 01Introductory Page
page.content: The square is 2/3 covered by mainly deciduous woods over undulating land from 50-300ft. above sea-level. The rest is farmed as pasture for sheep and cows with some apple,pear and plum orchards. The main area of population is in the NE corner, being ribbon development along the A290, halfway between Whitstable and Canterbury. This is Honeyhill with a farm of the same name, pub, nursery and shop, tropical bird garden and houses. The other concentration of houses is part of Dargate (NW corner) with 20 houses, transport depot, motor museum, pub and disused chapel. Other habitations are mainly farms and cottages scattered on the road that runs SW to NE across the square. The majority of farmed land follows this road. An area of the east Woodland is owned by the R.S.P.B. and another by the Nature Conserv.Council.
